2026-07-17  source: DONE. Device 86 sourced, closing the last gap; all seven devices now rest on a
            published document and the two-standards-of-evidence split is closed.
            86 is a lockout relay = a latch, no number to reproduce, so the BEHAVIOUR is the source.
            Primary: GE 850 "Non-volatile Latches", p.4-414, rendered at 9x and read as an IMAGE (it
            is a table; text layers stitch tables). GE's stated purpose is the lockout function
            verbatim: "a permanent logical flag ... does not reset when the relay reboots ...
            permanently blocking relay functions ... until a deliberate HMI action resets the latch."
            Published truth table, Reset Dominant: SET on -> ON; SET off & RESET off -> PREVIOUS STATE
            (the latch); RESET on -> OFF; SET+RESET -> OFF (reset wins, so it can always be cleared);
            and non-volatile, so it survives a power-down exactly like a hand-reset lockout.
            🔴 NAMING KEPT HONEST: the 850 labels no element "86". It DOES document the latch
            primitive an 86 is built from, and separately names an external "86-T" lockout relay
            (p.4-357). Do NOT confuse this with the 850's "Reclosure Lockout" (p.4-377), which is the
            autoreclose shot-limit state sharing only the word. 86 as a device number is C37.2, cited
            by number only.
            PROVENANCE: same v2.0x (2017) docs.ips.us mirror as 25, but LOW stale-risk for a
            structural reason: a reset-dominant non-volatile latch is a LOGIC PRIMITIVE, not a tuned
            setpoint a firmware revision retunes. Labelled anyway; current v4.3x login walled, unread.

